She moved more like an avalanche than a person, a dark wall ofearth shifting toward him.
He was the only thing between her and his mother.
Leo screamed with desperation.
His vision turned red.
Flames washedover the earthen woman, the walls, the locked doors.
And Leo lost consciousness.
She told him the warehouse had burned down.
His mother hadn’t made it out.
The paramedic said she was sorry,but Leo felt hollow.
He’d lost control, just like his mother had warned.
Her death was his fault.
The fire had started in the break room, they said, right where Leo was standing.
He’dsurvived by some miracle, but what kind of child locked the doors of his mother’s workplace, knowing she was inside, and started a fire?Later, his neighbors at the apartment complex told the police what a strange boy he was.
They talked about the burned handprints on the picnictable.
They’d always known something was wrong with Esperanza Valdez’s son.
His Aunt Rosa called him a diablo and shouted at the social workers to take him away.
So Leo went to his firstfoster home.
A few days later, he ran away.
Some foster homes lasted longer than others.
He would joke around, make a few friends, pretend that nothingbothered him, but he always ended up running sooner or later.
It was the only thing that made the pain better—feeling like he was moving, getting fartherand farther away from the ashes of that machine shop.
He hadn’t thought about Tía Callida, or the sleeping woman wrapped in earthen robes,for a long time.
Our enemy wakes.
It’s time to stop running.
Hera had been watching him his entire life.
Somehow, she’d known that one day she would need him.
Leo wasn’t sure.
But he knew he was meant to go on this quest.
Jason’s prophecy warned themto beware the earth, and Leo knew it had something to do with that sleeping woman in the shop, wrapped in robes of shifting dirt.
He might meet his father, or even get to avenge his mother’s death.
He’d promised Jason a flying ride.
There wasn’t time to build something that complicated.
He needed a quicker solution.
He needed a dragon.
Owls hooted, and something far away hissed like a chorus of snakes.
Leo had nothing—no sword, noflashlight, no help.
He could turn around now and tell everyone he’d been joking.
Psych! Nyssa could go on the questinstead.
